rectal examination reveals a 2 cm defect in the rectal mucosa above an intact external anal sphincter.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate classification of this injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Second-degree tear","Buttonhole tear","Third-degree tear","Fourth-degree tear","First-degree tear"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes a buttonhole tear, which is a defect in the rectal mucosa that occurs while the external anal sphincter remains intact. This is a rarer type of perineal trauma where despite the apparently minimal external trauma, this injury must be classified as a fourth-degree tear due to the breach in the rectal mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EButtonhole tear\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct classification for this injury. While not part of the standard classification system, it specifically describes this type of injury where there is a defect in the rectal mucosa with an intact external anal sphincter. Any injury to the anal mucosa is significant and requires specialist repair. For future deliveries, recommendations would be similar to those for a fourth-degree tear, including consideration of elective caesarean section to avoid the risk of recurrence and further complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E involve only the vaginal epithelium and perineal skin. This classification would significantly underestimate the severity of a buttonhole tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E extend into the perineal muscles but not the anal sphincters. This classification would miss the serious nature of the rectal mucosal defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThird-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E involve disruption of the anal sphincter complex but not the anal epithelium. While serious, this classification does not capture the presence of the rectal mucosal defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFourth-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E are defined as injuries involving both the anal sphincter complex and anal epithelium. While a buttonhole tear involves the anal epithelium, the intact sphincter makes this a specific subtype that requires recognition for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key learning point is that thorough examination of the entire birth canal, including digital rectal examination, is essential after vaginal delivery. Buttonhole tears may not be apparent on external examination but require urgent surgical repair to prevent complications such as rectovaginal fistula formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A buttonhole tear is a defect in the rectal mucosa with an intact external anal sphincter and should be classified as a fourth-degree tear.","Any injury to the anal mucosa is significant and requires specialist repair to prevent complications such as rectovaginal fistula.","Recommendations for future deliveries after a buttonhole tear are similar to those for fourth-degree tears, including consideration of elective caesarean section."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). The management of third- and fourth-degree perineal tears. Green-top Guideline No. 29 [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2015 [cited 2024 Nov 21]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/media/5jeb5hzu/gtg-29.pdf","Ramar CN, Vadakekut ES, Grimes WR. Perineal lacerations. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 [cited 2024 Nov 21]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559068/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16026"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T13:25:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T14:24:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8717"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108626"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1374"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Labour","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-09-20T00:15:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-03T14:30:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"group